  mainEntity: [
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is AI optimization for product listings?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'AI optimization for product listings is the practice of structuring product data, schema markup, and listing content so that AI engines can accurately extract, represent, and cite specific products in generated answers. It covers both on-page structured data (Product schema in JSON-LD) and the written content of product listings — specifications, descriptions, and comparison elements — that AI retrieval systems parse when answering product-specific queries.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is the minimum Product schema required for AI citation?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'The minimum viable Product schema for AI citation includes: @type "Product", name, brand (as a Brand type), description, sku, image (as an ImageObject), offers (with price, priceCurrency, availability, and url), and aggregateRating (with ratingValue, bestRating, worstRating, and reviewCount). Missing any of these properties creates data gaps that reduce citation confidence. For products with multiple variants, each variant should have its own offers block with accurate price and availability.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'How should product descriptions be written to maximise AI extraction?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Product descriptions optimised for AI extraction should open with a single declarative sentence defining what the product is and its primary use case. Follow with a specifications section using structured HTML (a table or definition list) that lists key attributes consistently. Avoid marketing language that does not convey factual information. Include a "best suited for" or "ideal use case" statement that matches the natural language patterns of AI shopping queries. Descriptions of 150 to 300 words with this structure perform significantly better in AI extraction tests than longer, prose-heavy descriptions.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Do product data feeds (Google Merchant Centre, Meta Catalogue) affect AI citation?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Yes, indirectly. Google Merchant Centre feeds inform Google Shopping, which in turn provides product data signals to Google AI Overviews and Gemini when those systems are answering shopping-intent queries. A product in Google Merchant Centre with complete, accurate attributes is more likely to appear in Google AI Overviews shopping panels than a product not in the feed. Meta Catalogue and other feed platforms have less direct influence on current AI citation, but contribute to the breadth of platforms on which product data exists — which strengthens training data representation over time.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'How do variant products affect AI citation?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Product variants — different sizes, colours, or configurations of the same base product — require careful structured data handling to perform well in AI citation. Each meaningful variant should have its own offers block within the parent Product schema, with accurate price and availability per variant. If variants have significantly different specifications (e.g., different technical performance per size), those differences should appear in the listing content. AI systems that encounter a single product listing with no variant distinction may cite incorrect availability or pricing when answering specific variant queries.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is the difference between Product schema on a DTC site and a marketplace listing?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
