              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <div class="prose-dark mt-8">
          <h3>The aggregateRating Gap</h3>
          <p>
            The most common Product schema deficiency across ecommerce sites is a missing or unpopulated <code>aggregateRating</code>.
            Many sites implement the base Product schema but omit review data — either because their review system is not connected
            to schema generation, or because they have fewer than the minimum review count they consider worthy of display.
            AI engines treat <code>aggregateRating</code> as a quality proxy for commercial queries. A product with no rating data
            in schema is materially less likely to be cited in "best X" answers than an equivalent product with a populated
            <code>ratingValue</code> and <code>reviewCount</code>, even if the underlying review data is modest.
          </p>
          <p>
            For a complete implementation guide with worked JSON-LD examples for all product schema types, see our technical guide to
            <a href="/schema-markup-ai/">schema markup for AI</a>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 3 -->
      <section id="listing-content" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Writing Product Listing Content for AI Extraction</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Product listing descriptions written for AI extraction follow a specific structural pattern that maximises the probability of accurate citation.</strong>
          The pattern contrasts sharply with traditional product copywriting, which typically opens with a brand statement or lifestyle hook.
          AI retrieval systems need factual, extractable content from the opening sentence.
        </p>

        <h3>The Declarative Opening Pattern</h3>
        <p>
          Every product description should open with a single sentence that defines the product and its primary use case in plain, factual language.
          The pattern is: "[Product name] is a [category] [designed/built/intended] for [primary use case]."
          For example: "The Vortex 500 is a full-frame mirrorless camera designed for amateur photographers transitioning from DSLR systems."
          This sentence provides an AI system with everything it needs to accurately represent the product in a generated answer without reading further.
        </p>
        <p>
          Follow the opening sentence with two to four sentences covering the product's key distinguishing features — the attributes that make it
          different from competitors. These should be specific and factual: sensor resolution, battery life, materials, certifications.
          Avoid comparative language without specifics ("best in class", "industry-leading") — AI systems cannot extract or verify these claims,
          and they reduce the citability of the surrounding content.
        </p>

        <h3>Use-Case Statements</h3>
        <p>
          Include an explicit "best suited for" or "ideal for" statement that names specific use cases in natural language.
          "Ideal for trail runners seeking a minimal drop shoe for technical terrain" or "best suited for home bakers who want consistent
          results without a professional oven". These statements directly match the query patterns used in AI shopping searches and
          dramatically improve citation frequency for long-tail, use-case-specific queries.
        </p>

        <h3>What to Avoid</h3>
        <p>
          Listing content that suppresses AI extraction includes: opening sentences that begin with brand statements or campaign language;
          dense paragraphs without clear factual claims; specifications embedded in prose rather than structured tables; and benefit statements
          that lack specific evidence. Marketing language does not reduce citation per se, but it reduces the density of extractable information
          per sentence — which makes the AI system's job harder and reduces citation confidence.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 4 -->
      <section id="specifications" class="anchor-top mb-16">
        <div class="prose-dark">
          <h2>Specifications and Structured Attributes</h2>
          <p>
            <strong>Product specifications presented in structured HTML tables are among the most reliably extracted content elements by AI retrieval systems.</strong>
            A specifications table provides clear attribute-value pairs that an AI system can parse directly — without needing to interpret
            prose context or infer what value applies to which attribute. This is particularly critical for technical products where
            specifications are the primary basis for comparison.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-8 space-y-6">

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">HTML Table Structure</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Specifications tables should use <code>&lt;th scope="row"&gt;</code> for attribute names and <code>&lt;td&gt;</code> for values,
              within a two-column <code>&lt;table&gt;</code>. Each row should be a single attribute. Avoid merging cells, using images
              to represent values, or embedding specifications in inline styles. AI retrieval systems parse standard HTML table structure;
              non-standard implementations reduce extraction reliability.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">additionalProperty Schema</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              The same specifications should be represented in structured data using <code>additionalProperty</code> within the
              Product schema, with each specification as a <code>PropertyValue</code> containing <code>name</code> and <code>value</code>.
              Duplicate representation — in both HTML and JSON-LD — reinforces the structured signal and is significantly more
              AI-extractable than either representation alone. For products with many specifications, prioritise the ten to fifteen
              attributes most relevant to common comparison queries.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-[var(--accent)]">Consistency Across the Catalogue</h3>
            <p class="mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">
              Specifications attributes should be consistent in naming and units across all products in a category. If one product
              uses "Weight: 250g" and another uses "Weight (grams): 250", AI systems may fail to compare them accurately in
              generated answers. Establish a controlled vocabulary for specification attributes per product category and enforce
              it across the entire catalogue. This consistency benefit extends to Google Merchant Centre feeds and comparison
              aggregators, as well as AI citation.
            </p>
          </div>

        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 5 -->
      <section id="feeds-and-catalogues" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Feeds, Catalogues, and Platform Distribution</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Product data feeds are a parallel channel through which AI systems access product information — independent of web crawling.</strong>
          Google Merchant Centre, Meta Commerce Manager, Microsoft Shopping, and Amazon Vendor/Seller Central all process product feeds that
          populate their respective shopping platforms. These platforms in turn feed AI engines — directly in Google's case, and indirectly
          through training data and retrieval indexing in others.
        </p>

        <h3>Google Merchant Centre and AI Overviews</h3>
        <p>
          Google Merchant Centre (GMC) feeds provide Google AI Overviews with product data that supplements web crawling. Products with
          complete GMC feed attributes — title, description, category, brand, GTIN, price, availability, images, and product highlights —
          are more likely to appear in Google AI Overviews shopping panels for relevant queries. Feed quality matters as much as feed
          completeness: a well-optimised GMC title follows the same declarative pattern as an AI-optimised product description — product name,
          key attribute, use case — rather than the promotional titles often submitted for text ad campaigns.
        </p>

        <h3>Feed Attribute Quality</h3>
        <p>
          The attributes that most directly influence AI citation via GMC feeds are: <code>product_type</code> (Google's taxonomy category),
          <code>google_product_category</code> (the standardised Google taxonomy ID), <code>brand</code> (consistent with the brand name
          in Product schema), <code>gtin</code> (for cross-platform deduplication), and <code>product_highlight</code> (up to five
          bullet-point highlights that appear in Shopping panels). <code>product_highlight</code> is particularly underutilised;
          well-written highlights following the declarative pattern significantly improve citation accuracy in AI-generated comparisons.
        </p>

        <h3>Marketplace Listings</h3>
        <p>
          Marketplace product listings on Amazon, eBay, and similar platforms contribute to AI citation through two mechanisms:
          the marketplace's own structured data is indexed by AI crawlers, and editorial coverage referencing marketplace listings
          contributes to training data. For brands that sell through Amazon, the Amazon listing title, bullet points, and A+ content
          are all potential AI citation sources — particularly for AI systems that use Amazon's product catalogue as a data source.
          Optimising Amazon bullet points using the declarative + specification pattern improves citation quality on platforms that
          retrieve Amazon content.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 6 -->
      <section id="variants" class="anchor-top prose-dark mb-16">
        <h2>Handling Product Variants Correctly</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>Product variants — multiple sizes, colours, or configurations sold under a single product listing — are one of the most common sources of AI citation error for ecommerce brands.</strong>
          When variant data is not correctly represented in structured data, AI systems either cite the default variant (often the first listed,
          regardless of relevance to the query) or aggregate variant data incorrectly — producing wrong pricing or availability in generated answers.
        </p>

        <h3>Individual Offers per Variant</h3>
        <p>
          For products with meaningful variant differences — particularly price or availability — implement a separate <code>Offer</code> block
          within the Product schema for each significant variant. Each offer should include the variant-specific <code>price</code>,
          <code>availability</code>, and a <code>url</code> pointing to the canonical URL for that variant. An AI system encountering
          a product schema with a single offer block for a multi-variant product cannot distinguish between a sold-out size and an
          available size — and may cite the product as "in stock" when the relevant variant is not.
        </p>

        <h3>Variant-Specific Content</h3>
        <p>
          Where variants differ in meaningful technical specifications — different battery life per model tier, different weight per size,
          different compatibility per edition — those differences should appear in the visible content of the variant page or variant section.
          AI queries that target specific variant attributes ("lightest version of X", "X with longest battery life") can only be answered
          correctly if the variant-level specification data exists in the page content and structured data for the relevant variant.
        </p>
      </section>

